comments.text:
+fishworshipper Other than the ability to take the form of mist, none of 
the traits that you attributed with vampires are accurate. It appears that 
you get too much of your information from pop culture, and of the Twilight 
variety at that.

Let's just go over a few things. For starters, vampires die when in direct 
sunlight, are repelled and harmed by commonly found items (garlic, 
crucifixes, holy water, etc.), are almost constantly tortured by an 
unquenchable thirst for blood, and are incapable of entering someone's home 
without their permission (similar to some stories about witches). 
Furthermore, vampires would logically be unable to get an erection, so that 
in itself is a pretty big negative.

Werewolves, traditionally, were simply shapeshifters who could take the 
form of a wolf at will, although they often required a certain item to do 
so. They were also hindered by the fact that they'd be trapped in their 
human form if their clothes were stolen. I'd definitely choose werewolf 
over vampire.

During medieval times, it was a common belief that vampires were werewolves 
who hadn't been burned after death.﻿
comments.author: Bob Bobson

comments.text:
+fishworshipper Care to explain how exactly I'm ignorant?

Yes, Dracula could shapeshift and did, typically into a bat or wolf. That's 
not really relevant, though, seeing as vampires existed in myth far before 
Bram Stoker's character based on Vlad III (Vlad the Impaler).

One may be illegal, but nothing is physically preventing you from doing so. 
You're definitely not incapable of it. You're also not currently driven by 
a lust for human blood, so not being able to enter someone's home unless 
you're invited doesn't present nearly as large of an obstacle to you. I 
love garlic, but you're entitled to your own opinion. It would really suck 
having a weakness commonly found in a jar of Prego, though. I don't really 
have that last issue, but I'd definitely prefer it to never being able to 
have sex again.

Good to see that you detest Twilight.
comments.author: Bob Bobson

comments.text:
Seems like you're the ignorant one here.

Dracula, the archetypal vampire, could shapeshift at will. He didn't die in 
sunlight, but was merely weakened in it. If he drank someone's blood, his 
age reversed, making him effectively immortal. Not being able to enter 
someone's abode unless invited and being repulsed by garlic are two traits 
that I already effectively have, because one's illegal and the other is 
disgusting, so not much changes there. Not being able to get an erection is 
infinitely better than always getting unwanted ones, so that's a positive 
rather than a negative for me.
